** Ursula K. Le Guin on Power=2C Oppression=2C Freedom=2C and How Imaginat=
ive Storytelling Expands Our Scope of the Possible (https://www.brainpicki=
ngs.org/2016/05/06/ursula-k-le-guin-freedom-oppression-storytelling/?mc_ci=
d=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1590300068/braipick-20=E2=80=9CWe m=
ust always take sides=2C=E2=80=9D Elie Wiesel urged in his spectacular Nob=
el Prize acceptance speech (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/12/10/elie-=
wiesel-nobel-prize-speech/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . =E2=
=80=9CNeutrality helps the oppressor=2C never the victim. Silence encourag=
es the tormentor=2C never the tormented.=E2=80=9D And yet part of the huma=
n tragedy is that despite our best intentions and our most ardent ideals=
=2C we often lull ourselves into neutrality in the face of injustice =E2=
=80=94 be it out of fear for our own stability=2C or lack of confidence in=
 our ability to make a difference=2C or that most poisonous foible of the=
 soul=2C the two-headed snake of cynicism and apathy. How=2C then=2C do we=
 unmoor ourselves from a passivity we so masterfully rationalize=2C rememb=
er that =E2=80=9Cinjustice anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere=2C=
=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/18/martin-luther-king-let=
ter-from-birmingham-city-jail/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and=
 rise to that awareness with moral courage
and imagination?

That=E2=80=99s what Ursula K. Le Guin (b. October 21=2C 1929) examines in=
 one of the many magnificent pieces in The Wave in the Mind: Talks and Ess=
ays on the Writer=2C the Reader=2C and the Imagination (http://www.amazon.=
com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1590300068/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[=
UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/wave-in-the-mind-=
talks-and-essays-on-the-writer-the-reader-and-the-imagination/oclc/5241818=
3&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=
=94 that trove of her clear-headed=2C bright-hearted wisdom on subjects as=
 eclectic and essential as gender (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/10/1=
7/ursula-k-le-guin-gender/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C the=
 sacredness of public libraries (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/11/06/=
ursula-k-le-guin-libraries/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C th=
e magic of real human conversation (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/10/=
21/telling-is-listening-ursula-k-le-guin-communication/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22=
b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and what beauty really means (https://www.brainp=
ickings.org/2014/10/21/ursula-le-guin-dogs-cats-dancers-beauty/?mc_cid=3D2=
4aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

Ursula K. Le Guin by Benjamin Reed

In an ennobling and pleasurably unnerving essay titled =E2=80=9CA War With=
out End=2C=E2=80=9D which Le Guin describes as =E2=80=9Csome thoughts=2C w=
ritten down at intervals=2C about oppression=2C revolution=2C and imaginat=
ion=2C=E2=80=9D she writes:

My country came together in one revolution and was nearly broken by anothe=
r.

The first revolution was a protest against galling=2C stupid=2C but relati=
vely mild social and economic exploitation. It was almost uniquely success=
ful.

Many of those who made the first revolution practiced the most extreme for=
m of economic exploitation and social oppression: they were slave owners.

The second American revolution=2C the Civil War=2C was an attempt to prese=
rve slavery. It was partially successful. The institution was abolished=2C=
 but the mind of the master and the mind of the slave still think a good m=
any of the thoughts of America.

When these dominant narratives become so deeply embedded in a society=2C L=
e Guin suggests=2C even those whom they oppress end up internalizing them.=
 (I think of James Baldwin=2C who observed in his terrific conversation wi=
th Nikki Giovanni (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/04/james-baldwin-=
nikki-giovannis-dialogue/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) : =E2=80=
=9CWhat the world does to you=2C if the world does it to you long enough a=
nd effectively enough=2C you begin to do to yourself. You become a collabo=
rator=2C an accomplice of your own murderers=2C because you believe the sa=
me things they do.=E2=80=9D)

Phillis Wheatley

In turning to the subject of resistance to oppression=2C Le Guin invokes t=
he memorable words of the poet and onetime slave Phillis Wheatley=2C who w=
rote in 1774: =E2=80=9CIn every human Breast=2C God has implanted a princi=
ple=2C which we call Love of Freedom; it is impatient of Oppression=2C and=
 pants for Deliverance.=E2=80=9D Le Guin considers the discomfiting parado=
x at the heart of this abiding truth:

All that is good in the institutions and politics of my country rests on i=
t.

And yet I see that though we love freedom we are mostly patient of oppress=
ion=2C and even refuse deliverance.

I see a danger in insisting that our love of freedom always outweighs what=
ever force or inertia keeps us from resisting oppression and seeking deliv=
erance.

If I deny that strong=2C intelligent=2C capable people will and do accept=
 oppression=2C I=E2=80=99m identifying the oppressed as weak=2C stupid=2C=
 and inept.

If it were true that superior people refuse to be treated as inferiors=2C=
 it would follow that those low in the social order are truly inferior=2C=
 since=2C if they were superior=2C they=E2=80=99d protest; since they acce=
pt an inferior position=2C they are inferior. This is the comfortably taut=
ological argument of the slave owner=2C the social reactionary=2C the raci=
st=2C and the misogynist.

In a counterpoint to Kierkegaard=E2=80=99s ideas about the power of the mi=
nority (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/11/26/kierkegaard-individual-cr=
owd-conformity-minority/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Le Gu=
in reality-checks the distribution of power throughout human history:

The ruling class is always small=2C the lower orders large=2C even in a ca=
ste society. The poor always vastly outnumber the rich. The powerful are f=
ewer than those they hold power over. Adult men hold superior status in al=
most all societies=2C though they are always outnumbered by women and chil=
dren. Governments and religions sanction and uphold inequality=2C social r=
ank=2C gender rank=2C and privilege=2C wholly or selectively.

Most people=2C in most places=2C in most times=2C are of inferior status.

And most people=2C even now=2C even in =E2=80=9Cthe free world=2C=E2=80=9D=
 even in =E2=80=9Cthe home of the free=2C=E2=80=9D consider this state of=
 affairs=2C or certain elements of it=2C as natural=2C necessary=2C and un=
changeable. They hold it to be the way it has always been and therefore th=
e way it must be. This may be conviction or it may be ignorance; often it=
 is both. Over the centuries=2C most people of inferior status have had no=
 way of knowing that any other way of ordering society has existed or coul=
d exist =E2=80=94 that change is possible. Only those of superior status h=
ave ever known enough to know that; and it is their power and privilege th=
at would be at stake if the order of things were changed.

But beyond the truism that those in power are better equipped to stay in p=
ower=2C Le Guin argues that there is a larger failure of moral imagination=
 keeping oppressive power structures in place. She writes:

We have good reason to be cautious=2C to be quiet=2C not to rock the boat.=
 A lot of peace and comfort is at stake. The mental and moral shift from d=
enial of injustice to consciousness of injustice is often made at very hig=
h cost.

[=E2=80=A6]

The last words of the Mahabharata are=2C =E2=80=9CBy no means can I attain=
 a goal beyond my reach.=E2=80=9D It is likely that justice=2C a human ide=
a=2C is a goal beyond human reach. We=E2=80=99re good at inventing things=
 that can=E2=80=99t exist.

Maybe freedom cannot be attained through human institutions but must remai=
n a quality of the mind or spirit not dependent on circumstances=2C a gift=
 of grace=E2=80=A6 My problem with it is that its devaluation of work and=
 circumstance encourages institutional injustices which make the gift of g=
race inaccessible. A two-year-old child who dies of starvation or a beatin=
g or a firebombing has not been granted access to freedom=2C nor any gift=
 of grace=2C in any sense in which I can understand the words. We can atta=
in by our own efforts only an imperfect justice=2C a limited freedom. Bett=
er than none. Let us hold fast to that principle=2C the love of Freedom=2C=
 of which the freed slave=2C the poet=2C spoke.

Echoing Susan Sontag=E2=80=99s assertion that =E2=80=9Ccourage is as conta=
gious as fear=2C=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/12/05/susan-=
sontag-on-courage-and-resistance/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 Le Guin considers the irreversible Rube Goldberg machine of awareness and=
 action through which injustice is confronted and countered:

The shift from denial of injustice to recognition of injustice can=E2=80=
=99t be unmade. What your eyes have seen they have seen. Once you see the=
 injustice=2C you can never again in good faith deny the oppression and de=
fend the oppressor. What was loyalty is now betrayal. From now on=2C if yo=
u don=E2=80=99t resist=2C you collude. But there is a middle ground betwee=
n defense and attack=2C a ground of flexible resistance=2C a space opened=
 for change. It is not an easy place to find or live in.

Illustration from The Harvey Milk Story (https://www.brainpickings.org/201=
5/04/13/picture-book-biographies/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 =2C a picture-book biography of the slain LGBT rights pioneer

Reflecting on Audre Lord=E2=80=99s assertion that one can=E2=80=99t disman=
tle the master=E2=80=99s house with the master=E2=80=99s tools=2C which Le=
 Guin considers a =E2=80=9Crich and dangerous=E2=80=9D metaphor=2C she wri=
tes:

Power not only corrupts=2C it addicts. Work becomes destruction. Nothing i=
s built. Societies change with and without violence. Reinvention is possib=
le. Building is possible. What tools have we to build with except hammers=
=2C nails=2C saws =E2=80=94 education=2C learning to think=2C learning ski=
lls?

In a sentiment that calls to mind the great cellist Pau Casals=E2=80=99s w=
onderful notion of making this world worthy of its children (https://www.b=
rainpickings.org/2016/03/10/pablo-casals-joys-and-sorrows-jfk/?mc_cid=3D24=
aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Le Guin adds:

Are there indeed tools that have not been invented=2C which we must invent=
 in order to build the house we want our children to live in? Can we go on=
 from what we know now=2C or does what we know now keep us from learning w=
hat we need to know? To learn what people of color=2C the women=2C the poo=
r=2C have to teach=2C to learn the knowledge we need=2C must we unlearn al=
l the knowledge of the whites=2C the men=2C the powerful?

The most powerful such tool=2C Le Guin argues=2C is the imagination =E2=80=
=94 the ability and willingness to imagine alternatives to reality as we k=
now it=2C which is always the first step toward making different and bette=
r realities possible. She points to storytelling as the most powerful use=
 of the imagination in expanding our scope of the possible:

Utopia=2C and Dystopia=2C are intellectual places. I write from passion an=
d playfulness. My stories are neither dire warnings nor blueprints for wha=
t we ought to do. Most of them=2C I think=2C are comedies of human manners=
=2C reminders of the infinite variety of ways in which we always come back=
 to pretty much the same place=2C and celebrations of that infinite variet=
y by the invention of still more alternatives and possibilities.

[=E2=80=A6]

To me the important thing is not to offer any specific hope of betterment=
 but=2C by offering an imagined but persuasive alternative reality=2C to d=
islodge my mind=2C and so the reader=E2=80=99s mind=2C from the lazy=2C ti=
morous habit of thinking that the way we live now is the only way people c=
an live. It is that inertia that allows the institutions of injustice to c=
ontinue unquestioned.

Fantasy and science fiction in their very conception offer alternatives to=
 the reader=E2=80=99s present=2C actual world. Young people in general wel=
come this kind of story because in their vigor and eagerness for experienc=
e they welcome alternatives=2C possibilities=2C change. Having come to fea=
r even the imagination of true change=2C many adults refuse all imaginativ=
e literature=2C priding themselves on seeing nothing beyond what they alre=
ady know=2C or think they know.

In a sentiment evocative of Susan Sontag=E2=80=99s beautiful thoughts on s=
torytelling and what it means to be a moral human being (https://www.brain=
pickings.org/2015/03/30/susan-sontag-writing-storytelling-at-the-same-time=
/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Le Guin considers the task o=
f imaginative storytelling and its ultimate reward:

The exercise of imagination is dangerous to those who profit from the way=
 things are because it has the power to show that the way things are is no=
t permanent=2C not universal=2C not necessary. Having that real though lim=
ited power to put established institutions into question=2C imaginative li=
terature has also the responsibility of power. The storyteller is the trut=
hteller.

[=E2=80=A6]

We will not know our own injustice if we cannot imagine justice. We will n=
ot be free if we do not imagine freedom. We cannot demand that anyone try=
 to attain justice and freedom who has not had a chance to imagine them as=
 attainable.

Complement this particular portion of the wholly indispensable The Wave in=
 the Mind (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1590300068/braipick-20?m=
c_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C which is titled after Virginia=
 Woolf=E2=80=99s metaphor for consciousness (https://www.brainpickings.org=
/2014/10/23/virginia-woolf-a-wave-in-the-mind/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) and which remains one of the most redemptive and rereadable=
 books I=E2=80=99ve ever encountered=2C with Albert Camus on cultivating s=
trength of character (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/12/28/albert-camu=
s-almond-trees-character/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Rebe=
cca Solnit on the grounds for hope in our moral imagination (https://www.b=
rainpickings.org/2016/03/16/rebecca-solnit-hope-in-the-dark-2/?mc_cid=3D24=
aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and Neil Gaiman on how stories change us=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/06/16/neil-gaiman-how-stories-last/?m=
c_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Le Guin=E2=80=99s=
 advice on writing (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/10/ursula-k-le-g=
uin-writing-advice/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


