** What Makes a Good Life: Revelatory Learnings from Harvard=E2=80=99s 75-=
Year Study of Human Happiness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/23/ha=
rvard-grant-study-robert-waldinger-ted/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNI=
QID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0674503813/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D24a=
a1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CThe good life is one inspired by love and guided by knowledge=2C=
=E2=80=9D Bertrand Russell wrote in his 1925 treatise on the nature of the=
 good life and how we limit our happiness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2=
015/05/18/bertrand-russell-what-i-believe-love/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) . For the whole of human history up to that point=2C such qu=
estions had been left entirely to his ilk =E2=80=94 the philosophers =E2=
=80=94 and perhaps to the occasional poet.

By the following decade=2C a team of visionary researchers at Harvard had=
 enlisted the tools of science in wresting tangible=2C measurable=2C actio=
nable answers to this perennial question of the good life. So began the St=
udy of Adult Development at the Harvard Medical School=2C better known as=
 the Grant Study =E2=80=94 the longest-running study of human happiness. B=
eginning in 1938 as a counterpoint to the disease model of medicine=2C the=
 ongoing research set out to illuminate the conditions that enhance wellbe=
ing by following the lives of 268 healthy sophomores from the Harvard clas=
ses between 1939 and 1944. It was a project revolutionary in both ambition=
 and impact=2C nothing like it done before or since.

For some necessary perspective on medicine in the 1930s: Having not yet un=
covered the structure of DNA=2C we knew close to nothing about genetics; m=
ental health was a fringe concern of the profession=2C with the Diagnostic=
 and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders still two decades away; the mi=
crobiome (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/10/i-contain-multitudes-ed=
-yong/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) was an inconceivable flight=
 of fancy. Little progress had been made since Walt Whitman=E2=80=99s pres=
cient case for the grossly underserved human factors in healthcare (https:=
//www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/19/walt-whitman-hospital-visits/?mc_cid=3D=
24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and the question of what makes for a good l=
ife was cautiously left to philosophy. It=E2=80=99s hard for the modern mi=
nd to grasp just how daring it was for physicians to attempt to address it=
=2E

But that=E2=80=99s precisely what the Harvard team did. There are=2C of co=
urse=2C glaring limitations to the study =E2=80=94 ones that tell the lame=
ntable story of our cultural history: the original subjects were privilege=
d white men. Nonetheless=2C the findings furnish invaluable insight into t=
he core dimensions of human happiness and life satisfaction: who lives to=
 ninety and why=2C what predicts self-actualization and career success=2C=
 how the interplay of nature and nurture shapes who we become.

In this illuminating TED talk=2C Harvard psychologist and Grant Study dire=
ctor Robert Waldinger =E2=80=94 the latest of four generations of scientis=
ts working on the project =E2=80=94 shares what this unprecedented study h=
as revealed=2C with the unflinching solidity of 75 years of data=2C about=
 the building blocks of happiness=2C longevity=2C and the meaningful life.

https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/23/harvard-grant-study-robert-waldin=
ger-ted/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

The clearest message that we get from this 75-year study is this: Good rel=
ationships keep us happier and healthier.

For a deeper dive into the significance and legacy of the Grant Study proj=
ect=2C see the revelatory book Triumphs of Experience: The Men of the Harv=
ard Grant Study (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0674503813/braipic=
k-20?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.w=
orldcat.org/title/triumphs-of-experience-the-men-of-the-harvard-grant-stud=
y/oclc/792887462&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UN=
IQID]) ) by Harvard psychologist George E. Vaillant =E2=80=94 Waldinger=E2=
=80=99s predecessor=2C who spent thirty years as director of this revoluti=
onary study =E2=80=94 then revisit his Harvard peer Daniel Gilbert on how=
 our present illusions hinder our future happiness (https://www.brainpicki=
ngs.org/2014/06/18/daniel-gilbert-happiness-future-self/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea2=
2b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and pioneering immunologist Esther Sternberg on how=
 our relationships affect our immune system (https://www.brainpickings.org=
/2015/10/07/esther-sternberg-stress-relationships/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_=
eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


