** Hermann Hesse on the Three Types of Readers and Why the Most Transcende=
nt Form of Reading Is Non-reading (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/1=
1/hermann-hesse-types-of-readers/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0374511098/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D24a=
a1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Categories are how we navigate the world (http://www.npr.org/programs/invi=
sibilia/384065938/the-power-of-categories?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[U=
NIQID]) =2C for better or for worse =E2=80=94 this impulse toward organiza=
tion helps us (to borrow Umberto Eco=E2=80=99s wonderful phrase (https://w=
ww.brainpickings.org/2011/12/22/umberto-eco-on-lists/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&=
mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) make infinity comprehensible=2C but its perilous fli=
pside is the seedbed of stereotypes (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/04=
/09/the-hidden-brain-shankar-vedantam/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) .

Hermann Hesse (July 2=2C 1877=E2=80=93August 9=2C 1962) placed this parado=
xical nature of categories at the heart of his taxonomy of the three types=
 of readers =E2=80=94 a sort of fluid hierarchy of reading modes=2C which=
 he outlined in an altogether magnificent 1920 essay titled =E2=80=9COn Re=
ading Books.=E2=80=9D It was later included in My Belief: Essays on Life a=
nd Art (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0374511098/braipick-20?mc_c=
id=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.o=
rg/title/my-belief-essays-on-life-and-art/oclc/834601&referer=3Dbrief_resu=
lts?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=94 the terrific Hesse=
 anthology that gave us the beloved writer and Nobel laureate on why the b=
ook will never lose its magic (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/07/th=
e-magic-of-the-book-hermann-hesse-my-belief/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D=
[UNIQID]) .

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0374511098/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D24a=
a1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

From ancient mythology to modern psychology=2C Hesse notes=2C the human ex=
perience is strewn with such taxonomies of character. He writes:

We have an inborn tendency to establish types in our minds and to divide m=
ankind according to them. [But] however advantageous and revealing such c=
ategories may be=2C no matter whether they spring from purely personal exp=
erience or from attempting a scientific establishment of types=2C at times=
 it is a good and fruitful exercise to take a cross section of experience=
 in another way and discover that each person bears traces of every type w=
ithin himself and that diverse characters and temperaments can be found as=
 alternating characteristics within a single individual.

There are=2C Hesse argues=2C such distinct temperaments when it comes to o=
ur personality as readers:

Since you may take a completely different attitude toward anything in the=
 world=2C so you may toward the book.

Half a century before E.B. White proclaimed that children are =E2=80=9Cthe=
 most attentive=2C curious=2C eager=2C observant=2C sensitive=2C quick=2C=
 and generally congenial readers on earth=2C=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpi=
ckings.org/2015/02/26/e-b-white-writing-for-children/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&=
mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Hesse offers a hierarchical taxonomy predicated on the=
 same sentiment. He outlines three key types=2C which can similarly coexis=
t within a single reader over the course of a lifetime=2C beginning with t=
he na=C3=AFve reader =E2=80=94 the reader who experiences a book merely as=
 content=2C be it intellectual or aesthetic:

Everyone reads na=C3=AFvely at times. This reader consumes a book as one c=
onsumes food=2C he eats and drinks to satiety=2C he is simply a taker=2C b=
e he a boy with a book about Indians=2C a servant girl with a novel about=
 countesses=2C or a student with Schopenhauer. This kind of reader is not=
 related to a book as one person is to another but rather as a horse to hi=
s manager or perhaps as a horse to his driver: the book leads=2C the reade=
r follows. The substance is taken objectively=2C accepted as reality. But=
 the substance is only one consideration! There are also highly educated=
=2C very refined readers=2C especially of belles letters=2C who belong ent=
irely to the class of the na=C3=AFve=E2=80=A6 What the material=2C setting=
=2C and action are to simple souls=2C the art=2C language education=2C and=
 intellectuality of the writer are to these cultivated readers.

[=E2=80=A6]

This kind of reader assumes in an uncomplicated way that a book is there s=
imply and solely to be read faithfully and attentively and to be judged ac=
cording to its content or its form. Just as a loaf of bread is there to be=
 eaten and a bed to be slept in.

He then turns to the second type of reader=2C which one might call (though=
 Hesse does not provide a concrete term) the imaginative investigator =E2=
=80=94 a reader endowed with childlike wonderment=2C who sees past the sup=
erficialities of content to plumb the depths of the writer=E2=80=99s creat=
ive impulse:

If one follows one=E2=80=99s nature and not one=E2=80=99s education one be=
comes a child again and begins to play with things; the bread becomes a mo=
untain to bore tunnels into=2C and the bed a cave=2C a garden=2C a snow fi=
eld. Something of this child-likeness=2C this genius for play=2C is exhibi=
ted by the second type of reader. This reader treasures neither the substa=
nce nor the form of a book as its single most important value. He knows=2C=
 in the way children know=2C that every object can have ten or a hundred m=
eanings for the mind. He can=2C for example=2C watch a poet or philosopher=
 struggling to persuade himself and this reader of his interpretation and=
 evaluation of things=2C and he can smile because he sees in the apparent=
 choice and freedom of the poet simply compulsion and passivity. This read=
er is already so far advanced that he knows what professors of literature=
 and literary critics are mostly completely ignorant of: the there is no s=
uch thing as a free choice of material or form.

[=E2=80=A6]

From this point of view the so-called aesthetic values almost disappear=2C=
 and it can be precisely the writer=E2=80=99s mishaps and uncertainties th=
at furnish much the greatest charm and value. For this reader follows the=
 poet not the way a horse obeys his driver but the way a hunter follows hi=
s prey=2C and a glimpse suddenly gained into what lies beyond the apparent=
 freedom of the poet=2C into the poet=E2=80=99s compulsion and passivity=
=2C can enchant him more than all the elegance of good technique and culti=
vated style.

Art by Maurice Sendak for The Big Green Book (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2015/06/04/the-big-green-book-robert-graves-maurice-sendak/?mc_cid=3D24a=
a1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by Robert Graves

Next comes the final type of reader=2C who is really a non-reader but rath=
er a dreamer and interpreter:

The third and last type of reader =E2=80=A6 is apparently the exact revers=
e of what is generally called a =E2=80=9Cgood=E2=80=9D reader. He is so co=
mpletely an individual=2C so very much himself=2C that he confronts his re=
ading matter with complete freedom. He wishes neither to educate nor to en=
tertain himself=2C he uses a book exactly like any other object in the wor=
ld=2C for him it is simply a point of departure and a stimulus. Essentiall=
y it makes no difference to him what he reads. He does not need a philosop=
her in order to learn from him=2C to adopt his teaching=2C or to attack or=
 criticize him. He does not read a poet to accept his interpretation of th=
e world; he interprets it for himself. He is=2C if you like=2C completely=
 a child. He plays with everything =E2=80=94 and from one point of view th=
ere is nothing more fruitful and rewarding than to play with everything. I=
f this reader finds a beautiful sentence in a book=2C a truth=2C a word of=
 wisdom=2C he begins by experimentally turning it upside down.

In a sentiment which Nobel-winning physicist Frank Wilczek would come to e=
cho nearly a century later in his assertion that =E2=80=9Cyou can recogniz=
e a deep truth by the feature that its opposite is also a deep truth=2C=E2=
=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/02/complementarity-frank-wil=
czek-a-beautiful-question/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Hesse a=
dds:

[This reader] has known for a long time that for each truth the opposite=
 also is true. He has known for a long time that every intellectual point=
 of view is a pole to which an equally valid antipole exists. He is a chil=
d insofar as he puts a high value on associative thinking=2C but he knows=
 the other sort as well.

But what grants this reader her or his superiority over the other types is=
=2C above all=2C a trained capacity for associative thinking that turns th=
e reading material into a springboard for indiscriminate curiosity from wh=
ich to leap far beyond the particular substance of the particular book. (A=
 quarter century later=2C the inventor Vannevar Bush would describe the sa=
me psychological orientation in his prescient vision for the type of perso=
n who would triumph in the Information Age (https://www.brainpickings.org/=
2012/10/11/as-we-may-think-1945/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 =E2=80=94 the person who can =E2=80=9Cfind delight in the task of establi=
shing useful trails through the enormous mass of the common record.=E2=80=
=9D) Hesse writes:

This reader is able=2C or rather each one of us is able=2C at the hour in=
 which he is at this stage=2C to read whatever he likes=2C a novel or gram=
mar=2C a railroad timetable=2C a galley proof from the printer. At the hou=
r when our imagination and our ability to associate are at their height=2C=
 we really no longer read what is printed on the paper but swim in a strea=
m of impulses and inspirations that reach us from what we are reading. The=
y may come out of the text=2C they may simply emerge from the type face. A=
n advertisement in a newspaper can become a revelation; the most exhilarat=
ing=2C the most affirmative thoughts can spring from a completely irreleva=
nt word if one turns it about=2C playing with its letters as with a jigsaw=
 puzzle. In this stage one can read the story of Little Read Riding Hood a=
s a cosmogony or philosophy=2C or as a flowery erotic poem. Or one can rea=
d the label =E2=80=9CColorado maduro=E2=80=9D on a box of cigars=2C play w=
ith the words=2C letters=2C and sounds=2C and thereby take a tour
through the hundred kingdoms of knowledge=2C memory=2C and thought.

Art by Maurice Sendak for The Big Green Book (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2015/06/04/the-big-green-book-robert-graves-maurice-sendak/?mc_cid=3D24a=
a1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by Robert Graves

Hesse addresses the potential protestation that using a book as the trigge=
r for a Rube Goldberg machine of interpretive associations is not =E2=80=
=9Creading=E2=80=9D at all =E2=80=94 for is it really reading to devour=
 =E2=80=9Ca page of Goethe unconcerned about Goethe=E2=80=99s intentions a=
nd meanings=E2=80=9D? The objector=2C he imagines=2C would accuse this rea=
ding mode of being =E2=80=9Cthe lowest=2C most childish and barbaric=E2=80=
=9D of all. The objection=2C he concedes=2C is a valid one. And yet it con=
tains within its validity the very point =E2=80=94 each mode of reading is=
 necessary for a full life=2C but it is insufficient in and of itself. =E2=
=80=9CIt must be emphasized that no one of us need belong permanently to a=
ny one of these types=2C=E2=80=9D he cautions. In a passage that calls to=
 mind Umberto Eco=E2=80=99s notion of the antilibrary (https://www.brainpi=
ckings.org/2015/03/24/umberto-eco-antilibrary/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Hesse writes:

The reader at the their stage is no longer a reader. The person who remain=
ed there permanently would soon not read at all=2C for the design in a rug=
 or the arrangement of the stones in a wall would be of exactly as great a=
 value to him as the most beautiful page full of the best-arranged letters=
=2E The one book for him would be a page with the letters of the alphabet.

So be it: the reader at the last stage is really no longer a reader at all=
=2C he doesn=E2=80=99t give a hoot about Goethe=2C he doesn=E2=80=99t read=
 Shakespeare. The reader in the last stage simply doesn=E2=80=99t read any=
 more. Why books? Has he not the entire world within himself?

Half a century before Agnes Martin=E2=80=99s memorable observation that=
 =E2=80=9Cwe all have the same inner life [but] the artist has to recogni=
ze what it is=2C=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/03/31/agnes-=
martin-john-gruen-interview/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Hesse=
 adds:

Whoever remained permanently at this stage would not read any more=2C but=
 no one does remain permanently at this stage. But whoever is not acquaint=
ed with this stage is a poor=2C an immature reader. He does not know that=
 all the poetry and all the philosophy in the world lie within him too=2C=
 that he greatest poet drew from no other source than the one each of us h=
as within his own being. For just once in your life remain for an hour=2C=
 a day at the third stage=2C the stage of not-reading-any-more. You will t=
hereafter (it=E2=80=99s so easy to slip back) be that much better a reader=
=2C that much better a listener and interpreter of everything written. Sta=
nd just once at the stage where the stone by the road means as much to you=
 as Goethe and Tolstoy=2C you will thereafter gain from Goethe=2C Tolstoy=
=2C and all poets infinitely more value=2C more sap and honey=2C more affi=
rmation of life and of yourself than ever before. For the works of Goethe=
 are not Goethe and the volumes of Dostoevsky are not
Dostoevsky=2C they are only an attempt=2C a dubious and never successful a=
ttempt=2C to conjure up the many-voiced multitudinous world of which he wa=
s the central point.

Hesse likens this type of reading to a dream (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2015/03/16/mark-strand-dreams-collected-poems/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_ei=
d=3D[UNIQID]) =2C or perhaps to what Stephen King has termed =E2=80=9Ccre=
ative sleep.=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/10/14/stephen-ki=
ng-on-writing-and-creative-sleep/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 Dreaming transmogrifies the raw material of reality=2C gathered in our wa=
king life=2C into fanciful creations of the consciousness set free from th=
e constraints of reality. Similarly=2C this type of reading uses the actua=
l text on the page as raw material for the imaginative meanderings of the=
 mind. Hesse writes:

A dream is the opening through which you see into the content of your soul=
=2C and this content is the world=2C no more and no less than the world=2C=
 the whole world from your birth up to today=2C from Homer to Heinrich Man=
n=2C from Japan to Gibraltar=2C from Sirius to the Earth=2C from Red Ridin=
g Hood to Bergson. =E2=80=94 And to the extent that your attempt to write=
 down your dream is related to the world that embraces that dream=2C so th=
e work of an author is related to what he tired to say.

[=E2=80=A6]

Without having recognized this=2C be it only a single time=2C in all its i=
nfinite fullness and inexhaustible significance=2C you stand handicapped b=
efore every poet and thinker=2C you take for the whole what is a small par=
t=2C you believe in interpretations that barely touch the surface.

[=E2=80=A6]

The third stage at which you are most yourself will put an end to your rea=
ding=2C will dissolve poetry=2C will dissolve art=2C will dissolve world h=
istory. And yet unless you intuitively know this stage=2C you will never r=
ead any book=2C any science or art except as a schoolboy reads his grammar=
=2E

Hesse=E2=80=99s My Belief (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/03745110=
98/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C it bears repeat=
ing=2C is a transcendent read in its entirety. Complement this particular=
 fragment with Virginia Woolf on how to read a book (https://www.brainpick=
ings.org/2013/03/06/virginia-woolf-how-should-one-read-a-book/?mc_cid=3D24=
aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Patti Smith on the two types of masterpie=
ces (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/11/02/patti-smith-favorite-books-m=
-train/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C C.S. Lewis on why we r=
ead (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/11/26/c-s-lewis-literature-reading=
-books/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and a very old Robert=
 Graves=E2=80=99s subversive celebration of how books transform us (https:=
//www.brainpickings.org/2015/06/04/the-big-green-book-robert-graves-mauric=
e-sendak/?mc_cid=3D24aa1ea22b&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C illustrated by a ver=
y young Maurice Sendak.


